{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640360"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:15:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:15:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17820"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17820"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.96,0.02,0,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10534"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116751"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10534"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17820"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98738"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5083"},{"type":"tags","id":"9894"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24578"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24602"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116751"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary surfactant is essential for normal respiratory function. It is produced by specialised cells in the alveoli and begins appearing during foetal development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of pulmonary surfactant?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Facilitates gas exchange across alveolar membrane","Reduces surface tension at air-liquid interface","Protects against inhaled pathogens","Maintains alveolar pH balance","Prevents fluid accumulation in alveolar space"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary surfactant is a complex mixture of lipids and proteins that lines the alveoli. Its primary function is to \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduce surface tension at the air-liquid interface\u003C/strong\u003E within the alveoli. This action prevents alveolar collapse, particularly at the end of expiration when alveolar radii are smallest, and thereby reduces the work of breathing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile surfactant is crucial for maintaining alveolar patency, which is necessary for gas exchange, it does not directly \u003Cstrong\u003Efacilitate gas exchange across the alveolar membrane\u003C/strong\u003E. Surfactant proteins do have some immune functions, but their primary role is not to \u003Cstrong\u003Eprotect against inhaled pathogens\u003C/strong\u003E. Alveolar pH is maintained through ventilation and systemic buffer systems, not by surfactant, so it does not \u003Cstrong\u003Emaintain alveolar pH balance\u003C/strong\u003E. Finally, while preventing alveolar collapse helps maintain a dry alveolar space, the primary regulation of fluid balance is governed by osmotic and hydrostatic pressures, meaning surfactant does not directly \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevent fluid accumulation in the alveolar space\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurfactant is produced by type II alveolar cells and consists mainly of phosphatidylcholine and other phospholipids. Deficiency of surfactant is a major cause of respiratory distress syndrome in premature infants.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pulmonary surfactant reduces surface tension in alveoli, preventing collapse during expiration.","Surfactant is composed primarily of phosphatidylcholine and other phospholipids.","Surfactant is produced by type II alveolar cells and appears in foetal lungs around 24-28 weeks gestation."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora GJ, Mellifont R, Derrickson B, Burkett B, Peoples G, D D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition. 2nd ed. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019.","West JB, Luks AM. West\u2019s respiratory physiology: the essentials. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Wolters Kluwer; 2015. Chapter 7; p. 117."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98738"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17820"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98738"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-30T15:01:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-30T15:01:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10534"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116751"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":